The paper discusses the design of an empirical study to compare the usability of concurrent programming languages, which falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) and programming languages (cs.PL) sub-categories. The study also involves evaluating the comprehension and debugging of existing programs, which could be related to distributed computing (cs.DC) and logic in computer science (cs.LO). Additionally, the paper addresses the issue of bias in the study, which could be relevant to human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
